english:
  title: Record of the Spring Pavilion Pot-Tossing Game
  author: Choe Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In my youth, when I first began reading the classics, I came to understand that the game of pot-tossing was a ritual through which gentlemen moderate the pleasures between guest and host. Yet I never fully grasped its mechanics. When I later saw Director Sima Guang's illustrated guide, I gained some understanding, but lacked learned friends to question and refine my knowledge. Growing up on the coast, far from the refined scholars of the Central Plain, I regretted never having the chance to apprentice myself in earnest.

    In the spring of 1321, I had the fortune to journey to the Yuan capital on official business. As I awaited my appointment, I lodged with Hong Jungeui of Liaodong and others in a dwelling east of the city. To pass the idle hours, I borrowed a pot and arrows from Jungeui's kinsman and tried the game myself—and found great joy in it. But once I received my commission and returned home to assume office, I was consumed with duties and had no leisure to pursue it further.

    Now, having withdrawn from service due to illness for more than a decade, I find myself with time on my hands. I care not for games of chance, nor do I play musical instruments. Though I read widely, I have found little else to delight me. Only this game of the pot dwells constantly in my heart. Does it not draw us toward the cultivation of virtue and the ordering of the mind—a practice too precious to abandon?

    Yet my household possessed no pot, and none among our scholars kept one either. Though I cherished this art, I was powerless to pursue it. Then came Choe Chun-heon of Spring Pavilion—a man devoted to ancient learning and filial piety. Troubled that the young studied broadly without proper guidance, he gathered the works of the Cheng and Zhu philosophers to instruct them. But fearing endless tension without relief, he procured a pot from afar, believing it essential. He would summon those eager to learn, teach them by diagram, and the courtyard became filled with the spirit of spring breeze by the Yi waters. Would such care and such diligence be possible without deep devotion?

    In times to come, when the promising youth of the East engage in study and rest, learning what they have not yet known, should they suddenly blossom in splendor, we shall know they have been transformed by Master Choe's influence. How can we not admire this?

    Others have already inscribed their praise and composed their verses. What more could I add? I merely set down here the reasons for my own love of this game and the circumstances of Master Choe's establishment of it, as a simple record.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Pot-tossing (投壺) was an ancient Chinese game and ritual practiced by gentlemen, involving tossing arrows into a pot from a distance, symbolizing both skill and virtue.
  - key: ''
    value: Sima Guang (司馬光, 1019-1086), known as Director Sima Wenzheng, was a renowned Song dynasty statesman and historian whose illustrated guide to the game was influential.
  - key: ''
    value: The year 1321 corresponds to the Yuan Dynasty period Zhizhi (至治) era, when Choe Hae traveled to the Yuan capital as a Korean envoy.
  - key: ''
    value: The Cheng and Zhu philosophers refer to the neo-Confucian thinkers Cheng Yi and Zhu Xi, whose teachings were foundational to East Asian scholarly discourse.
